    - ⚠️ Minor note: `ProvidersTab.tsx` uses a custom `EmptyProvidersState`
    component instead of the shared `EmptyState` component from
    `@/components/shared`. This is acceptable but could be refactored for
    better consistency.

    ## 2. Data Layer Integration
    - ✅ Components use EXISTING hooks from
    `apps/gui/src/queries/settings.ts`.
    - ✅ Components use EXISTING schemas from
    `apps/gui/src/types/schemas/settings.ts`.
    - ✅ No duplicate data fetching.
    - ✅ Mutations use the optimistic update pattern (`.mutate()` is used for
    create/update/delete instead of `.mutateAsync() + await`). The dialog
    closes immediately upon submission.

    ## 3. Component Quality
    - ✅ `SettingsPage` exports `Component()` for React Router lazy loading.
    - ✅ Components use shared components (`PageHeader`, `StatusBadge`,
    `EmptyState`).
    - ✅ No hardcoded colors — all via CSS variables / Tailwind classes.
    - ✅ Proper TypeScript types used (no `any`).
    - ✅ Loading states handled correctly (`isLoading` from React Query).
    - ✅ Error states handled.

    ## 4. Build + Tests
    - ✅ `cd apps/gui && npx tsc --noEmit` passes with no errors.
    - ✅ `cd apps/gui && npm run build` passes.
    - ✅ `cd apps/gui && npx playwright test e2e/settings.spec.ts` passes all
    8 tests.

    ## 5. Pattern Consistency
    - ✅ Import paths use `@/` aliases correctly.
    - ✅ Consistent with existing code patterns in the codebase.
    - ✅ E2E test route mocks use regex for workflows.

    ## Conclusion
    The implementation is solid, passes all tests, and adheres to the design
    and architectural guidelines. No major issues found.
